                                                                                                                                                              7-MS-PS1-4
MATTER AND ITS INTERACTIONS
                                                         Develop a model that predicts and describes changes in particle motion, temperature, and the state of a pure
            Performance Expectation                      substance when thermal energy is added or removed.
                                                         Emphasis is on qualitative molecular-level models of solids, liquids, and gases to show that adding or removing
                                                         thermal energy increases or decreases kinetic energy of the particles until a change of state occurs. Examples of
             Clarification Statement                     models could include drawings or diagrams. Examples of particles could include molecules or inert atoms such as
                                                         the noble gases. Examples of pure substances could include water, carbon dioxide, or helium.
        Science & Engineering Practices                                    Disciplinary Core Ideas                                          Crosscutting Concepts
1. Asking questions and defining problems                STRUCTURE AND PROPERTIES OF MATTER                                    CAUSE AND EFFECT
                                                         Gases and liquids are made of molecules or inert atoms (the noble     Cause and effect relationships may be used to predict
2. Developing and using models: Modeling in 6–8 builds   gases) that are moving about relative to each other. (MS.PS1A.c)
   on K–5 experiences and progresses to developing,                                                                            phenomena in natural or designed systems.
                                                         In a liquid, the molecules are constantly in motion and in contact
   using and revising models to describe, test, and      with others; in a gas, they are widely spaced except when they
   predict more abstract phenomena and design            happen to collide. In a solid, atoms are closely spaced and may
   systems.                                              vibrate in position but do not change relative locations. (MS.PS1A.d)
 • Develop and/or use a model to predict and/or describe The changes of state that occur with variations in temperature or
   phenomena.                                            pressure can be described and predicted using temperature and
                                                         pressure models of matter. (MS.PS1A.f)
3. Planning and carrying out investigations
                                                         The temperature of a system is proportional to the average
4. Analyzing and interpreting data                       internal kinetic energy and potential energy per atom or molecule
                                                         (whichever is the appropriate building block for the system’s
5. Using mathematics and computational thinking          material). The details of that relationship depend on the type
6. Constructing explanations and designing solutions     of atom or molecule and the interactions among the atoms in
                                                         the material. Temperature is not a direct measure of a system’s
7. Engaging in argument from evidence                    total thermal energy. The total thermal energy (sometimes called
                                                         the total internal energy) of a system depends jointly on the
8. Obtaining, evaluating, and communicating information
                                                         temperature, the total number of atoms in the system, and the
                                                         state of the material. (MS.PS.3A.c)
                                                         The term “heat” as used in everyday language refers both
                                                         to thermal energy (the motion of atoms or molecules within
                                                         a substance) and the transfer of that thermal energy from
                                                         one object to another. In science, heat is used only for this
                                                         second meaning; it refers to the energy transferred due to the
                                                         temperature difference between two objects. (MS.PS3A.e)
